Year = {{2002}},
Volume = {{76}},
Number = {{2}},
Pages = {{135-147}},
Month = {{APR-JUN}},
Abstract = {{Saint-John Perse's work, considered with a number of its intertexts
   (Shakespeare, Cesaire, Glissant, Camus) is a good illustration of the
   ambivalence of literary discourse vis-a-vis the colonial imaginary, its
   archetypes and mythologies. Perse, a Caribbean poet, reworks in
   ambiguous ways, such as demystifying irony or mournful eulogies, the
   colonial representations which were born mostly within the plantation
   world of the end of the 17th century: aristocratic ideals, dreams of
   purity, domination fantasies, utopian refoundations, historical
   destinies on a cosmic scale...Thus, the object of poetic writing is
   one's own relationship to the imaginary: it foregrounds its own
   negation, in order to pursue being and the real.}},
