Pages = {{719-729}},
Month = {{DEC}},
Abstract = {{In this essay, I review the works of filmmakers Bill Morrison and
   Gregorio Rocha and contextualize their work within a growing
   apocalyptic cultural movement of film preservationists who identify as
   ``orphanistas.{''} As orphanistas they struggle to reshape and
   reproduce cultural memory and heritage through reviving
   ``orphans{''}-films abandoned by their makers. Moving images mimic
   cognitive memory, yet, depending on reproductive technologies, copies
   of moving images may organize mass publics and influence cultural
   imaginaries. Traditionally considered conservative, preservation in the
   midst of destruction is not only a creative but also an avant-garde act
   of breathing new life into storytelling and the reproduction of
   cultural memory. In this essay, I discuss how the surrealist works of
   Morrison and Rocha radically confront dominant cultural imaginings of
   race and nation, and I argue that film preservation has the potential
   of being socially transformative. An interview with Gregorio Rocha
   follows.}},
