   first memorized the layout of a building containing 10 rooms with 24
   objects. Participants then received mental imagery instructions and
   imagined how they walked through the building from one room to another.
   The authors manipulated Euclidean distance involved in these imaginary
   motions: Spatial distance measured in centimeters on the layout was
   either short or long. Independently, they varied categorical distance:
   The motions led through one room or two rooms. The time needed to
   imagine motions and response times to test probes indicated that both
