Year = {{2003}},
Volume = {{33}},
Number = {{122}},
Pages = {{7-17}},
Abstract = {{Widening the scope of the inter-personal frame of the
   ``master-disciple{''} pair, what is meant here is the setting of this
   relation back into its collective dimension. Indeed, one of the major
   features of the 19th century seems to have been the socialization of
   hierarchic relations between writers, as the result of the trend of
   literary ``schools{''}. The ``master{''} then becomes the ``school
   master{''}: as for the disciples, they are now given hierarchically
   organized functions. This new situation, made blatant after 1830
   because of Hugo's overwhelming stature, raised an outburst of protest
   against the ``literary royals{''} and their blinded henchmen. These
   protestations gross and unfair as they were, are not very enlightening
   as the new hierarchic relations ruling the literary world: a space that
   is less open, more governed by rules and hierarchy that one may
   imagine, considering the ``imperialism of the genius{''} endowing
   ``leaders{''} with imaginary functions that are more gratifying than
   those of ``masters{''}: kings, emperors, ``literary officers{''}, sect
   leaders... But the masters are soon back on stage when, with the ebb of
   romanticism, the generation of the ``Parnasse{''} (Banville, Flaubert)
   insists anew on the necessity of the literary apprenticeship more than
   on the ``sacre de l'ecrivain{''} - from mysticism back to technique. In
   a literary world that is thus re-centered, the master can once again
   have a pedagogic dimension and the authority of the inimitable model,
   to the detriment of his charismatic aura.}},
