   in the one and the other is significant. In Jezabel Bloch depicted an
   imaginary pure world of the Jews with diatonic, simple melodies and
   painted the pagan Jezebel with the lush chromaticism associated with
   Oriental sensuality; in Schelomo he interpreted the chromatic,
   augmented-second-ridden style as expressive of Jewishness. Schelomo
   thus fulfilled the expectations of Bloch's audiences by playing into
   stereotypes of Jewish music. Ironically then, the anti-Semitism that
   was a major factor in driving Bloch to find a particularly Jewish voice
   also inspired the corroboration of a musical style that, like the
