   young, and Sawrey, a village in Yorkshire where she spent her life
   until she died. Her tales are the reflection of her ambition as a woman
   of letters and her struggle to achieve a certain integrity. They bring
   out her inner self, with its anxieties, distress, frustrations and her
   fight to exorcise them. They are a sort of outlet, accounts of the
   childhood experiences of the people of her times, and above all, a
   means to understand the mechanisms existing in this period and to
   dismantle them. Her work focuses on recurrent themes such as the
   importance of maternal law, desire or the hero's journey into the self.
   More important are the masculine and feminine images that appear
   through the tales, creating a dialectic of power that consists, at the
   same time, of a movement towards freedom and a regression towards
   archaisms. So, Beatrix Potter's work oscillates between conflicts and
   freedom, subversions and archaisms. The psychological dimension can't
