Pages = {{373-390}},
Month = {{JUL-SEP}},
Abstract = {{To touch on fiction is to touch on one of the sensitive spots of
   politics. For is not politics itself the place par excellence where
   fiction if found? This can be understood in various ways: there is the
   fiction which is a pretence or a deception, of course, but also fiction
   as the fable, narrative or story of a people, of a nation or of
   humanity. Better yet, does not fiction have a place at the heart of the
   political system, in laws and in power? Pascal stressed the sense in
   which fiction works from the inside towards obedience to the law, as
   well as its very status as law-as a mask for the violence which is at
   its origin. From another point of view, Hobbes attests how a juridical
   fiction-that of the fictitious man, the civic person-is at the heart of
   the institutional definition of the modern state in terms of
   representation ({''}fictitious,{''} here, not meaning false or unreal
   in any way). Politics appears as a place where there are multiple
   relationships between the real and the imaginary, as long as we are
   careful not to reduce this pair of notions unilaterally to those of
   true and false. Politics involves various types of relationship between
   the imaginary and the real: sharing, superimposition, transformation of
   the one into the other. In order to attempt to untie the multiple
   political links between the real and the imaginary, I shall first of
   all examine the different strata where the political problem of fiction
   arises. I shall then consider the way fiction works in the structure of
   power and the art of government with a view to answering the question,
   ``Can politics liberate itself from fiction?{''} or again, ``Is it
   possible to eradicate fiction from politics?{''} Two forms of fiction
   will be studies: fiction understood as illusion or deception, and
   fiction as transparency.}},
ISSN = {{0003-9632}},
Unique-ID = {{ISI:000165411100002}},
}

