   strategy, designed to correct norm misperceptions, has been correlated
   with a decrease in reported consumption in the general college
   population. However, it has had little or no impact among Greek
   students, the group that consumes the most alcohol. The authors
   investigated and subsequently found three possible flaws in the
   application of the social norms strategy that may account for the
   failure to decrease binge drinking among fraternity men: there is no
   predominant, healthy drinking norm in this population; students are
   influenced more by people within their network(s) than by others; and
