   future society, was contemporary with other imaginary utopian urban
   schemes drawn up in avant-garde circles internationally in the 1960s
   and the artist continued to develop it until 1974. Constant's
   ``situationist city{''} represented one of the earliest radical
   challenges to the institutionalized architecture of the post-war
   period. The aim was to transcend mere functionalism and envisage the
   urban milieu as an ``arca for participatory recreation,{''} a kind of
   labyrinth providing scope for diversion.
