Pages = {{343-354}},
Month = {{JUN}},
Abstract = {{Reformulation of adolescent egocentrism suggests that personal fable
   and imaginary audience ideations extend into adulthood. To test this
   proposition, adolescents (aged 14-18) and adults (aged 20-89) completed
   subscales of the adolescent egocentrism, self consciousness and
   interpersonal reactivity scales. An across scale comparison first
   ensured that adolescent egocentrism measures were comparable across
   age. Next, MANOVAs revealed higher egocentrism scores for adolescents
   us. adults (p < 0.05), but no difference between adolescents and
   younger (19-30) adults after splitting adults into younger (19-30),
   middle (31-59) and older (60+) subgroups. Results suggest that personal
   fable and imaginary audience are not confined to adolescence. (C) 2000
   The Association for Professionals in Services for Adolescents.}},
